the second half as Washington beat No. 6 Stanford 92-68 on Thursday

article.headline: Huskies improve to 12-0 on home court
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Giuliana Mendiola couldn't remember a tougher
week of practice as the Washington Huskies prepared for No. 6
Stanford.

	   "We were killing each other in practice,'' Mendiola said after
the Huskies won 92-68 on Thursday night to remain unbeaten at home.

	   "I never saw so many bodies on the ground,'' she said. "I was
matched against my sister and we were tearing each other's eyes
out.''

	   Mendiola scored 13 of her 20 points in the second half for the
Huskies (18-6 overall, 10-4 Pac-10), who bounced back against the
Pacific-10 leader after dropping two league games last week in Arizona.
They also reversed a loss at Stanford in the teams' first game this
season on Jan. 18, and improved to 12-0 at home.

	   Mendiola, Washington's skilled 5-foot-11 junior point guard,
shot 8-for-11, including 4-for-5 from 3-point range, while getting
seven assists and five rebounds.

	   The Huskies lost by 13 points at Arizona, and six at Arizona
State.

	   With four games left, Washington probably can't catch Stanford
in the Pac-10 race, but the Huskies thought they proved a point.

	   "This was huge,'' said Mendiola, whose teammates include older
sister Gioconda Mendiola, a reserve junior guard. "We showed a lot
of heart and we beat a great team. This will give us confidence.''

	   In the first Stanford-Washington game, the Cardinal outrebounded
the Huskies by 27.

	   "We got killed on the boards the last time we played 'em,''
Mendiola said.

	   Washington coach June Daugherty sent that message to her players
all week.

	   "The No. 1 thing was we had to be physical and we had to
outrebound them,'' she said. "Our post people didn't give up their
inside position the entire game.''

	   Daugherty said the Huskies sent a message to Stanford.

	   "We made a statement,'' she said. "There's no doubt about it.
Stanford's a good team and so are we.''

	   Andrea Lalum had 16 points and Loree Payne 13 for the Huskies,
who beat Stanford for the third time in their last four games in
Seattle.

	   The Cardinal (19-3, 11-2) were led by Nichole Powell's 20
points. Chelsea Trotter and Kelley Sujminski each had 14 for
Stanford, which had a four-game winning streak broken.

	   Washington shot 50 percent (13-for-26) from 3-point range and
committed only eight turnovers, while Stanford shot 5-for-19 from
behind the arc.

	   The Huskies led 49-38 at halftime after Stanford scored the
final eight points in the last 39 seconds of the first half. The
Cardinal got the help of a technical on the Washington bench, after
Daugherty slammed her clipboard onto the court.

	   The Cardinal were close at 63-52 after a basket by Trotter, but
Mendiola hit a 3-pointer and a 12-footer to put Washington in front
68-52 with 10:55 to play. Mendiola's 3-pointer with 6:06 gave the
Huskies a 77-54 advantage.

	   The 24-point defeat was the worst Pac-10 loss for Stanford since
March 9, 1991, when Oregon State defeated the Cardinal 87-61.
Stanford coach Tara VanDerveer was predictably unhappy with her
team's play.

	   "Washington played well, but we really helped them out,'' she
said. "Our defense was nonexistent. We gave up 49 points and eight
3s in the first half, and basically let them do anything they
wanted.

	   "Games get more physical as you get closer to (NCAA) tournament
time and we need to get more physical,'' she said.
